ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.
M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: Parent or child reported any tics in past three months?
Notes: 0 = no ; 1 = yes ; 3 = Not recorded - there is no way now to know

ElementDescription: Parent or child noticed any tics in past week (before intensively reviewing symptoms with the clinician)
Notes: 0 = no ; 1 = yes ; 3 = Not recorded - there is no way now to know

ElementDescription: Positive history of tics (parent or child reported tics in past week, including only after reviewing the Yale Global Tic Severity Scale survey)
Notes: 0 = no ; 1 = yes ; 3 = Not recorded - there is no way now to know

ElementDescription: Parent report: "If it weren't for this research study, would you be taking your child to the doctor now (or in the near future) because of his/her tics?"
Notes: 0 = no ; 1 = yes ; 3 = Not recorded - there is no way now to know

ElementDescription: Positive exam for tics (interviewer saw tics before Tic Suppression Paradigm)
Notes: 0 = no ; 1 = yes ; 3 = Not recorded - there is no way now to know

ElementDescription: Yale Global Tic Severity Scale impairment (pre-Tic Suppression Paradigm)
Notes: 0=None ; 10=Minimal.  Tics associated with subtle difficulties in self-esteem,   family life, social acceptance, or school/job functioning (infrequent upset or concern about tics vis a vis the future; periodic, slight increase in family tensions because of tics; friends or acquaintances may occasionally notice or comment about tics in an upsetting way).;  20=Mild.  Tics associated with minor problems in self-esteem, family life, social acceptance, or school/job functioning ; 30=Moderate.  Tics associated with some clear problems in self-esteem, family life, social acceptance, or school/job functioning (episodes of dysphoria, periodic distress and upheaval in the family, frequent teasing by peers or episodic social avoidance, periodic interference in school or job performance because of tics). ; 40=Marked.  Tics associated with major difficulties in self-esteem, family life, social acceptance, or school/job functioning. ; 50=Severe.  Tics associated with extreme difficulties in self-esteem, family life, social acceptance, or school or job functioning (severe depression with suicidal ideation, disruption of the family [separation/divorce, residential placement], disruption of social ties- severely restricted life because of social stigma and social avoidance, removal from school or loss of job).

ElementDescription: Tic-related impairment or marked distress (past week)? (clinical judgment)
Notes: 0 = no ; 1 = yes ; 3 = Not recorded - there is no way now to know

ElementDescription: Tic-related impairment or marked distress since last visit? (clinical judgment, FOLLOW-UP VISITS ONLY)
Notes: 0 = no ; 1 = yes ; 3 = Not recorded - there is no way now to know

ElementDescription: Tics observed on Tic Suppression Paradigm (checkbox)?
Notes: 0 = no ; 1 = yes ; 3 = Not recorded - there is no way now to know

ElementDescription: Yale Global Tic Severity Scale impairment (post-Tic Suppression Paradigm)
Notes: 0=None ; 10=Minimal.  Tics associated with subtle difficulties in self-esteem,   family life, social acceptance, or school/job functioning (infrequent upset or concern about tics vis a vis the future; periodic, slight increase in family tensions because of tics; friends or acquaintances may occasionally notice or comment about tics in an upsetting way).;  20=Mild.  Tics associated with minor problems in self-esteem, family life, social acceptance, or school/job functioning ; 30=Moderate.  Tics associated with some clear problems in self-esteem, family life, social acceptance, or school/job functioning (episodes of dysphoria, periodic distress and upheaval in the family, frequent teasing by peers or episodic social avoidance, periodic interference in school or job performance because of tics). ; 40=Marked.  Tics associated with major difficulties in self-esteem, family life, social acceptance, or school/job functioning. ; 50=Severe.  Tics associated with extreme difficulties in self-esteem, family life, social acceptance, or school or job functioning (severe depression with suicidal ideation, disruption of the family [separation/divorce, residential placement], disruption of social ties- severely restricted life because of social stigma and social avoidance, removal from school or loss of job).

ElementDescription: At follow-up visit: Tics completely gone for any period lasting 3 months since last visit?
Notes: 0 = no ; 1 = yes ; 3 = Not recorded - there is no way now to know
